{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636020","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636020"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:22:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:22:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17559"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17559","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17559"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.74,0.09,0.04,0.09,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10249"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71596"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10249"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17559"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57092"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5059"},{"type":"tags","id":"7142"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23957"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24152"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71596"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe substantia nigra (Image) is a key structure in the midbrain that appears dark due to the presence of neuromelanin pigment.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary neurotransmitter and projection target of substantia nigra neurons?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dopamine to striatum","Gamma-aminobutyric acid to cerebellum","Noradrenaline to cortex","Acetylcholine to hippocampus","Serotonin to thalamus"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Edopaminergic neurons of the substantia nigra project to the striatum\u003C/strong\u003E via the nigrostriatal pathway. These neurons are crucial for motor control and their loss leads to the movement disorders seen in Parkinson disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGamma-aminobutyric acid to cerebellum\u003C/strong\u003E - While the substantia nigra pars reticulata contains GABAergic neurons, they project to the thalamus and superior colliculus, not the cerebellum\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENoradrenaline to cortex\u003C/strong\u003E - Noradrenergic projections primarily originate from the locus coeruleus\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcetylcholine to hippocampus\u003C/strong\u003E - Cholinergic projections to the hippocampus come from the basal forebrain\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerotonin to thalamus\u003C/strong\u003E - Serotonergic projections primarily originate from the raphe nuclei\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe substantia nigra pars compacta contains the dopaminergic neurons that give this structure its characteristic dark appearance due to neuromelanin pigment. These neurons are particularly vulnerable to degeneration in Parkinson disease.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The substantia nigra is located in the midbrain and contains dopaminergic neurons that project to the striatum.","The substantia nigra pars compacta contains melanin-producing dopaminergic neurons giving it a dark appearance.","Loss of substantia nigra neurons is a hallmark of Parkinson disease."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","\u201cAn